name: 04-Model-Training-and-Evaluation
content:
Model Training, Evaluation and Prediction



Objective

The objective of this guide is to provide a comprehensive overview of how to train and evaluate a machine learning model for supplier selection. The chosen model is the Random Forest Classifier, an extension of the base Decision Tree Classifier.


Overview of Random Forest Classifier

Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that operates by constructing multiple Decision Trees during training. The final prediction is made by:

  • Classification: Taking the majority vote of the trees.
  • Regression: Taking the average prediction of the trees.

This approach improves performance and robustness compared to a single Decision Tree by reducing overfitting and increasing predictive accuracy.


1. Model Training

Approach

  • Data Preprocessing
  • Data Cleaning: Handle missing values, remove duplicates, and correct inconsistencies.
  • Feature Engineering: Create new features (e.g., cancellation rate, average order cost), encode categorical variables, normalize or standardize values as required.
  • Train-Test Split: Split the dataset into training (e.g., 70–80%) and testing (20–30%) subsets to evaluate generalization performance.
  • Model Training
  • Train a Random Forest Classifier by constructing multiple Decision Trees.
  • Each tree is trained on a bootstrap sample of the data with random feature selection at each split.
  • Hyperparameters to tune include:
  • n_estimators – Number of trees in the forest.
  • max_depth  – Maximum depth of each tree.
  • max_features– Number of features considered for splitting.
  • min_samples_split – Minimum samples required to split an internal node.
  • Target Variable
  • IsGoodSupplier: A binary classification variable indicating whether a supplier is Good (True) or Poor (False) based on business-defined thresholds.

2. Model Evaluation

  • After training, the model is evaluated using the test dataset.
  • Evaluation Metrics include:
  • Confusion Matrix – To visualize classification results.
  • Accuracy – Proportion of correctly classified suppliers.
  • Precision – Fraction of suppliers correctly identified as “Good.”
  • Recall – Fraction of actual “Good” suppliers that were correctly identified.
  • F1-Score – Harmonic mean of Precision and Recall, useful for imbalanced classes.
  • ROC-AUC – Measures the model’s ability to distinguish between Good and Poor suppliers.

-The data suggests that good suppliers tend to have higher order costs compared to bad suppliers, potentially due to factors like higher quality, premium services, or brand value. However, its important to note that there is significant variation within each supplier category, suggesting that other factors also influence order pricing.

-The data suggests that good suppliers tend to receive larger order quantities compared to bad suppliers, indicating a difference in customer preference or supplier performance. However, there is also variation within each category, suggesting that other factors may influence order quantity.


Part Quality Variation of Predicted Suppliers

-The data suggests that good suppliers tend to have higher part quality scores compared to bad suppliers, indicating a difference in quality performance. However, there is also variation within each category, suggesting that other factors may influence part quality.
